<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">a deep fissure, the sides of which are covered with Pine and Cedar: on climbing up the opposite side you are struck with wonder and surprise on finding yourself arrived at a Sandy plain of several leagues in extent, the side of which fronting the Lake is from 100 to 200 feet high and nearly perpendicular.  This plain terminates inland in a lake of water extremely black, which has no outlet but a little rill that passes through the fissure before mentioned.  In rowing along the front of this precipice, you see sand and Stones at every instant rolling down yet the beach never increases in breadth and heighth: there are two or three crevices in a distance of two leagues where people might save themselves in case of a sudden Storm of the lake, but you must almost inevitably lose your Canoe.  This apparently immense line of sandy mountain is found upon inspecting the several breaches made in its front to be a strong loam or clay, the surface of which is pulverized by the intense frosts of the winter, and the often no less intense heats of the Summer.</p>
